  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 하유(下帷) : '
    value: 장막(帳幕)을 내린다는 뜻. 《한서》 동중서전(董仲舒傳)에, “막을 내리고 경서를 강송(講誦)하여 제자들이 차례로 수업(授業)하는데, 어떤 때는 서로 얼굴을 못 보는 일도 있다.” 하였다. 뒤에 와서 깊이 들어가 글만 읽고 외간사를 간섭하지 않는 것을 하유공독(下帷攻讀)이라 한다.
  - key: '[주-D002] 돌을 뚫은 재주 : '
    value: 이광(李廣)은 한(漢)나라 명장(名將)이다. 북평(北平)에서 저물어 돌아오다가 돌을 호랑이로 잘못 보고 활을 쏘았는데, 화살촉이 그 돌에 박혀서 돌이 벌어졌다.
  - key: '[주-D003] 감당(甘棠) : '
    value: 아가위나무인데, 《시경》 소남(召南)의 편명(篇名)이다. 주(周)나라 소공(召公)이 남국을 순행하여 정사를 다스리고 농사를 권장하면서 아가위나무 아래서 쉬어갔었는데, 떠난 뒤에 백성이 그 덕화를 생각하여 그 나무를 사랑하면서 이 시를 지었다.
  - key: '[주-D004] 세류(細柳) : '
    value: 땅 이름인데, 한(漢)나라 장수 주아부(周亞夫)가 군영(軍營)을 두었다.
  - key: '[주-D005] 동고(童羖) : '
    value: 뿔 없는 염소를 동고(童羖)라 칭함. 《시경》 빈지초연(賓之初筵)에 “취해서 함부로 말하면 동고를 내놓게 한다.”[由醉之言 俾出童羖] 하였고, 그 주석에, “동고는 있을 수 없는 물건인데, 술에 취하는 것을 경계하기 위하여 구할 수 없는 물건을 벌로 내놓게 한 것이다.” 하였음. 여기서는 백성이 술에 방탕한 자가 없다는 말로 쓴 것임.
  - key: '[주-D006] 화악(華萼) : '
    value: 화악(華鄂)과 같은 말임. 《시경》 소아(小雅)상체(常棣)에, “상체의 꽃이여, 그 꽃봉오리 어찌 빛나지 않으리. 무릇 세상 사람은 형제보다 좋은 것이 없네.”[常棣之華 鄂不韚韚 凡今之人 莫如兄弟]라고 하였다. 그래서 세상에서 형제를 말하게 되면 매양 화악(華鄂)을 들어 비유함.
  - key: '[주-D007] 삼달(三達) : '
    value: 삼달존(三達尊)의 준 말임. 《맹자》 공손추(公孫丑)에, “천하에 달존(達尊) 셋이 있으니 연치(年齒)가 하나, 관직이 하나, 덕이 하나라.” 하였고 그 주에, “이 세 가지는 천하에서 공통으로 존래하는 것이다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D001] 令 : '
    value: 今
english:
  title: Stele Inscription for the Late Minister Hwang Ho-an of Joseon, with Preface
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Our dynasty, now approaching a century of rule, has enjoyed a time called the Great Peace. Among those called worthy ministers, scarcely one or two can be counted. Foremost among them stands Minister Hwang Ik-seong of Bangsong. To this day, people of all stations speak his praise without ceasing. What we call a lasting house is not merely the presence of ancient trees, but the presence of hereditary ministers—those like the descendants of Minister Ik-seong who, able to heal their father's wounds and sustain his legacy, bring no shame to those who bore them. Who would say this impossible? Such was Minister Ho-an, the late Vice-President of the State Council.

    The Minister bore the name Chi-sin, styled Maeng-chung. His lineage descended from the Long Water County of South Won Prefecture. Through his mother's line, he was the grandson of Choe Hong-yun, Minister of the Right under Goryeo. His ancestor Gyun-jeo received the posthumous rank of Councillor of State. His son, Goon-seo, served as Prefect of Kangnung and received posthumous rank of Left Minister. From Kangnung was born Leader of State Councillors and World-Teacher, later enfeoffed as Prince of South Won—this was Minister Ik-seong. Our Minister was his firstborn son. His mother was Lady Yang of Cheongju, daughter of the renowned scholar Yang Chen, and was posthumously honored as Lady of Virtue and Respect.

    From birth, the Minister possessed noble bearing. At merely five or six years of age, Scholar Yi, upon seeing him, declared: "Truly a prodigy!" As he grew, he applied himself diligently to learning without rest. When Great King Taejong learned of this, he said to Minister Ik-seong: "Your son's dedication to study rivals even that of Dong Zhongshu in his closed chamber of learning." The King bestowed upon him the name Dong-cho and appointed him Vice-Administrator of the Palace of Peace. Later, finding the name inappropriate to his generation, the King renamed him and promoted him to Director of the Palace Provisions Office. Through subsequent advancement, he served as Inspector of State Affairs, Recorder of the Board of Taxation, and Keeper of the Royal Wines—in each position earning recognition for his capable administration.

    In the fifteenth year of Xuande, he was appointed Senior Official of the Criminal Board. A powerful family had illegally enslaved fifty-odd common families through protracted litigation spanning decades. Upon taking office, the Minister resolved the matter in less than a month, restoring the victims to the register of free people. The public commended him greatly. The following year he rose to rank four and concurrently served as Aide to the Crown Prince. Later he returned to civilian service at rank three, becoming Administrator of Court Ritual and junior Keeper of Auspicious Objects. In the year Gyechuk, he was promoted to Vice-Director of the Secretariat, serving three years before dismissal due to circumstance. He was subsequently appointed Councillor of the Board of Rites, then transferred to the Board of Taxation. Soon elevated to the rank of Merit Subject, he became Vice-President of the Central Council, then transferred to become Magistrate of Seoul. The Sovereign, hearing of his ability to distinguish right from wrong without dispute, held him in great esteem and appointed him Provincial Inspector of Gyeonggi. The old practice had burdened magistrates with collecting tribute items without regard to what could be produced locally. The Minister petitioned the court to require only what each province naturally yielded, and the people benefited greatly. After his term, he became Magistrate of Kyongchang, then advanced through the Board of Taxation.

    In the year Gapja, he rose to rank three, became Minister of the Board of Taxation, and was reassigned as Magistrate of Seoul. In the year Mujin, he mourned his mother; in the year Imsin, he mourned Minister Ik-seong. Upon completing his mourning, he was appointed President of the Central Council. When dispatched as Envoy for the Imperial Celebration to the Ming Court, he succeeded in obtaining a copy of the long-sought History of Song, which had been requested unsuccessfully for generations. Upon his return, King Sejong, still in his position as Prince, reported this success to the ancestral temple and rewarded the Minister with a fine horse and saddle, elevating his retinue by one rank. The following year, while in his current post, he assumed additional duties as Supreme Military Commander.

    In the year Jeong-chuk of the Tianshun era, he was appointed Commander of the Military Forces of Chungcheong Province. There he demonstrated order in command and care for his soldiers, earning the reputation of an ancient general. From youth the Minister had earned renown for his archery. One day while training troops on a hunting expedition, an arrow he loosed pierced a beast and embedded itself so deeply in a dead tree that it could not be extracted. The soldiers marveled, saying: "Even the stone-piercing skill of General Li Guang could not surpass this!" He was recalled to serve as Magistrate of Inshun Prefecture, later transferred to Inshou Prefecture. In the year Sinsa, he advanced to the rank of Honor Subject and Vice-President of the Central Council, but soon was dismissed and lived in retirement for several years.

    In the year Byungsu of the Chenghua era, his younger brother Minister Yeol-seong asked a servant to secretly gather persimmons from the garden and invited the Minister to taste them. The Minister marveled at their sweetness, but upon returning home, found the garden stripped bare of the red fruit. He then understood he had been pleasantly deceived. Such playful jests between the brothers were common to them. When King Sejong visited the residence of Prince Yeong-ung, hearing of this, he remarked to the Prince: "The fraternal affection between my brothers should also be like this." He immediately summoned the Minister and appointed him Vice-President of the Central Council and Supreme Commander. At this time the Minister was seventy years old. He petitioned for retirement, but it was not granted. In the year Muuja, he was elevated to the rank of Great Honor. When the present Sovereign ascended the throne, he twice requested retirement, both times refused. In the year Gihae, he was appointed Vice-President of the State Council. The following year, again requesting retirement, the Sovereign sent royal lecturers to urge him to remain in office. Four years later, in the year Gapjin, he departed this world from illness at the age of eighty-eight.

    The Sovereign grieved so deeply that he suspended court for two days, dispatching an envoy to offer condolences and sacrifices. Though the Minister initially gained position through family distinction, he achieved prominence through generosity of spirit and diligent rectitude. Serving across multiple reigns, his rank and reputation grew ever greater, his character remaining constant from beginning to end. His longevity fell short of Minister Ik-seong's by only two years. Whenever King Sejong made a royal progress, he invariably appointed the Minister as regent of the capital, often praising him as comparable to the great general Guo Ziyi—for who else possessed such perfect union of loyalty, prosperity, long life, and a household brilliant with descendants?

    He took as first wife a daughter of Kim Ki, Minister of Royal Genealogy, and as second wife, a daughter of Hwang Sang. He fathered nine sons and five daughters. Those named for filial piety, fraternity, and virtue became distinguished officials in the military and civil service, their descendants multiplying in both lines to produce fifty-six grandsons and granddaughters, and fifty-one great-grandchildren of both sexes.

    Two years after the mourning period ended, his eldest son came requesting that I compose an inscription for his tomb. Unable to refuse, I have written these verses:

    Majestic Minister Hwang,
    Like phoenixes and cranes alighting gracefully—
    Grandson of Kangnung's lord,
    Son of great Minister Ik-seong.
    Not alone in noble countenance,
    But his virtue matched his handsome face.
    In youth aspiring to Dong Zhongshu's learning,
    The sovereign himself bestowed his name.
    Arrow-craft too he mastered well,
    Each shot meeting its mark with perfect aim.
    As Justice Official, straightening crooked cases,
    Public praise sang his deeds.
    His reputation brilliantly ascended,
    His long road stretched ever forward.
    Raised to posts of highest honor,
    Repeated promotion filled his years.
    In the capital, his verdicts settled all disputes,
    Ten thousand voices spoke his praise.
    The Red Lands knew his governance,
    Like willows drooping with mercy,
    While people lived free from coercion's bonds,
    And soldiers kept their modest posts.

    The History of Song, its myriad pages—
    He carried them home through imperial grace,
    And brought word to the ancestral shrine,
    Where the sovereign's bounty was proclaimed.
    With younger brother Yeol-seong,
    Their brotherly love ran deep,
    Playing with garden persimmons,
    They found profound contentment.
    Their joy resounded through nine palace levels,
    Urging harmony among all princes.

    When the jade carriage journeyed forth,
    The Minister always held the capital's command,
    Comparable to great General Guo,
    His fidelity constant from first to last.
    In teaching sons and grandsons,
    His household overflowed with virtue.
    On auspicious days in joyful gathering,
    All kinfolk met in harmony.
    Though few mortals unite the threefold honors
    With the fivefold blessings of prosperity,
    The Minister possessed them all—
    Unmatched through all recorded ages.

    Ten years bearing the Great Seal,
    He became the model for all people.
    Of hereditary service the sages spoke—
    Who but the Minister embodies this?

    Though he petitioned for rest,
    Heaven did not grant release.
    Yet his ending came with grace,
    And sorrow held a silver lining.
    Let all his descendants therefore resolve
    To preserve his memory eternal.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Dong Zhongshu's 'lowering of the screen' refers to his practice of drawing a curtain around himself to study classical texts in complete dedication, seeing no one for extended periods—a metaphor for intense scholarly devotion.
  - key: ''
    value: General Li Guang of the Han dynasty reportedly shot an arrow so forcefully at what he mistook for a tiger in the dim light that the arrowhead penetrated solid stone.
  - key: ''
    value: The Sweet Pear tree (Armeniaca mume) symbolizes benevolent governance from the poem in the Odes where the people cherished a minister's virtue even after his departure.
  - key: ''
    value: Zhouya Fu commanded troops at Xiliu, becoming a model of rigorous military discipline.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'hornless goat' is an impossible thing, used metaphorically to represent absence of drunken disorder among the people.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'flowery sepals' symbolize fraternal affection, derived from the Odes' celebration of brotherly bonds.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three honored ranks' are age, official position, and moral virtue—the three forms of eminence universally esteemed in the world.
